      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI < 5% for the primary quantity of interest (volume-averaged shear stress scalar) on the selected production mesh.",
      "rationale": "A formal three-mesh GCI study was conducted following Celik et al. (2008). GCI on the fine mesh was 1.8% for volume-averaged shear stress and 2.4% for peak wall shear stress. The medium mesh (5.8M elements) used in production runs achieved GCI of 3.1%, satisfying the 5% criterion. Discretization error is an accepted residual risk at this level; no further mesh refinement was deemed warranted given computational cost constraints and the margin below the acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid viscosity) match computational boundary conditions within measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Inlet flow rates were set to match FDA bench test conditions within ±2% using calibrated ultrasonic flow meters. Rotational speed was controlled to ±0.5 RPM. Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water, 36% by mass) viscosity was measured at 3.5 ± 0.1 mPa·s, matching the CFD fluid property input. Temperature was maintained at 37 ± 0.5°C throughout testing. All boundary conditions are within required correspondence levels for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted RH values and pressure-flow characteristics agree with experimental measurements within combined model and experimental uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "Predicted hydraulic head agreed with bench measurements to within 3.2% across all operating points (acceptance threshold 5%). Predicted RH values agreed with in-vitro measurements within ±12% relative error, well within the combined uncertainty budget of ±18% established from experimental repeatability and model uncertainty. The rank ordering of hemolysis across all 5 operating conditions was correctly reproduced. Output comparison results strongly support model adequacy for the intended COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The modeled QoI (relative hemolysis index RH, volume-averaged shear stress scalar) directly maps to the clinical and regulatory decision criterion.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH is the regulatory acceptance metric specified in the FDA guidance for CPB devices. The volume-averaged shear stress scalar feeds directly into the power-law hemolysis damage model used to compute RH. Both QoIs are therefore directly relevant to the COU decision. The mapping from CFD outputs to regulatory criterion is unambiguous and well established in the literature."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
